				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$r< 1~\upmu \mbox{m}$\end{document}) particles entering at high velocity (>40kms−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}${>}40~\mbox{km}\,\mbox{s}^{-1}$\end{document}).

Recently, a Meteoric Ablation Simulator (MASI) has been developed to test the predictions of ablation models like CABMOD (Bones et al. 2016; Gómez Martín et al. 2017). The MASI heats a meteoritic particle (r=20–200μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$r = 20\mbox{--}200~\upmu \mbox{m}$\end{document}) over a temperature ramp (up to 2800 K) that is programmed to match atmospheric entry for a specified velocity, and measures the absolute rates of evaporation of pairs of metal atoms (e.g. Na and Fe) using high repetition rate time-resolved laser induced fluorescence. MASI measurements confirm the model prediction of differential ablation i.e. the evaporation of relatively volatile elements such as Na and K before the main elements Fe, Mg and Si, and finally the refractory elements Ca, Ti and Al. However, the ablation profiles of individual species tend to be broader than predicted by a model such as CABMOD because meteorites do not consist of single mineral phases (Gómez Martín et al. 2017).

